<p>I am a <a href="https://history.virginia.edu/people/profile/csk5vf">doctoral candidate</a> at the University of Virginia. My teaching and scholarship examine the history of religion, politics, and culture in the United States. I am also interested in anti-racist pedagogy and digital history. I received my master‚Äôs degree in History and a graduate certificate in American Studies from UVA and my bachelor‚Äôs degree in History from Yale University. My dissertation, ‚Äú<a href="projects.html">Faith Networks: National Broadcasting and the Making of American Religion</a>,‚Äù explores religion and mass culture during the supposed ‚ÄúGolden Age‚Äù of radio. My writing has appeared in <a href="cv.html#cv-publications">various publications</a> including the <em>Yale Historical Review</em>, <em>Methodist Review</em>, and <em>Christian Century</em>. I recently received an ‚ÄúAccept with Revisions‚Äù for an article to be published in <em>Modern American History</em>. <a href="cv.html#cv-grants">Various organizations have supported my work</a> including the American Historical Association, the Renate Voris Fellowship Foundation, the American Jewish Historical Society, and the American Society of Church History. I also serve as the Editor of <a href="http://essaysinhistory.com"><em>Essays in History</em></a>, an open access journal for emerging historians.</p>

