<p>Connor S. Kenaston is a <a href="https://history.virginia.edu/people/profile/csk5vf">doctoral candidate</a>in History at the University of Virginia. Kenaston‚Äôs research examines the history of religion, politics, and culture in the United States. His dissertation project, ‚Äú<a href="projects.html">Faith Networks: National Broadcasting and the Making of American Religion</a>,‚Äù explores religion and mass culture during the supposed ‚ÄúGolden Age‚Äù of radio. His writings have appeared in various publications](cv.html#cv-publications) including the <em>Yale Historical Review</em>, <em>Methodist Review</em>, and <em>Christian Century</em>, and he recently received an ‚ÄúAccept with Revisions‚Äù for an article to be published in <em>Modern American History</em>. His work has been supported by <a href="cv.html#cv-grants">various organizations</a> including the American Historical Association, the Renate Voris Fellowship Foundation, the American Jewish Historical Society, and the American Society of Church History. Kenaston is also interested in anti-racist pedagogy and digital history. Since 2019, he has served as the Editor of <a href="http://essaysinhistory.com"><em>Essays in History</em></a>, an open access journal for emerging historians.</p>

<p>Kenaston holds an M.A. in History with a Certificate in American Studies from the University of Virginia and a B.A. in History from Yale University. In his spare time, he loves singing and exploring the outdoors. He is especially fond of kayaking the Greenbrier River in his home state of West Virginia. On weekends you can often find him helping out (or at least eating!) at his wife‚Äôs bakery, <a href="https://bowerbirdbakeshop.com/our-team">Bowerbird Bakeshop.</a></p>
